l. 19. exceptis quibusdam ciuitatibus. The roll 1 Ric. Ι (in which the system described in the Dialogus is well exemplified) begins with a sheet called the ‘ Rotulus de Honoribus’ containing the accounts of sixteen estates at that time in the king’s hands. In the 'body of the roll there are separate accounts for Waltham, Colchester, Orford, Lincoln‚ the honour of Tickhill‚ Higham, Northampton, Benson, the mines of Carlisle, the lands of Hasculf Musard and Hamo de Masei (in Notts and Derby), Windsor, Winchester, Southampton, Bosham, the honours of Arundel and Petworth‚ the land of Ingram de Mustrel (in Surrey), and Dover. Meons, which has a separate account under Henry 11, is by this time reduced to a part of the general account for Hampshire.
